  "content": "# Employment Agreement for Executive - Enhanced Drafting Workflow\n\nYou are drafting a comprehensive Employment Agreement for an executive-level position. This is a critical transactional document that will govern the employment relationship between a company and a senior executive, requiring careful attention to legal enforceability, market standards, and jurisdictional requirements.\n\n## Initial Information Gathering and Context\n\nBegin by searching the user's uploaded documents to identify all relevant factual information about this specific engagement. You need concrete details including the executive's name and title, the employer's legal entity name, the proposed start date, compensation structure (base salary, bonus targets, equity grants), benefits package details, reporting relationships, specific job responsibilities, and any special terms negotiated between the parties. Look for term sheets, offer letters, email correspondence, or prior drafts that contain these specifics. Every factual element you find should be attributed to its source document for verification purposes.\n\nIf critical information is missing after your document search, identify the gaps clearly so you can request clarification. Do not proceed with generic placeholder language when specific facts should be available.\n\n## Drafting the Parties and Introduction Section\n\nDraft a professional opening that identifies both parties with their complete legal names and addresses. For the employer, use the exact corporate entity name (including Inc., LLC, or other designation) and principal place of business. For the executive, include their full legal name and residence address. State the effective date of the agreement clearly, using the specific date found in your document search or requesting it if not available.\n\nThe introductory recitals should establish the context: that the employer desires to employ the executive in a senior leadership capacity, that the executive possesses unique skills and experience valuable to the employer, and that both parties wish to memorialize the terms of employment. Research current best practices for executive agreement introductions by examining authoritative legal resources and template providers to ensure your language reflects modern drafting standards while remaining jurisdiction-appropriate.\n\n## Position, Duties, and Reporting Structure\n\nDescribe the executive's position with specificity. Include the exact title, a detailed description of primary responsibilities and authority, the reporting relationship (typically to the Board of Directors or CEO), and the principal work location. Address whether the position requires full-time exclusive service or permits outside activities, board service, or consulting work with appropriate limitations.\n\nSearch your uploaded documents for any job description, organizational chart, or correspondence that details the scope of responsibilities. The duties section should reflect the actual expectations for this role, not generic executive language. If the executive will have specific operational responsibilities (such as overseeing particular divisions, managing certain budgets, or achieving defined objectives), incorporate those details.\n\nConsider including language about the executive's agreement to devote their best efforts and business judgment to the role, to comply with company policies and applicable laws, and to perform duties as reasonably assigned by the Board. Research state-specific standards for executive duty of loyalty and care to ensure your language aligns with applicable fiduciary principles.\n\n## Compensation, Benefits, and Equity\n\nThis section requires precise detail drawn from your document search. Specify the annual base salary with payment frequency (e.g., \"$350,000 per year, payable in accordance with the Company's standard payroll practices\"). Detail any signing bonus with payment timing and conditions.\n\nFor performance bonuses, describe the target amount or percentage, performance metrics or criteria, timing of determination and payment, and whether payment is discretionary or formula-based. If specific metrics exist in uploaded documents, incorporate them. If the bonus is discretionary, state the target clearly while preserving the employer's discretion.\n\nEquity compensation requires careful drafting. Specify the type of equity (stock options, restricted stock units, performance shares), the number of shares or units, the vesting schedule with cliff and incremental vesting periods, the exercise price for options, and the governing equity plan. Reference that equity grants will be subject to separate award agreements and the terms of the company's equity incentive plan. Include provisions addressing acceleration of vesting upon change of control or termination events if negotiated.\n\nDetail the benefits package including health insurance, retirement plan participation (401(k) with any employer match), life and disability insurance, paid time off (specifying vacation days, sick leave, and holidays), and any executive-specific perquisites such as car allowance, club memberships, or financial planning services. Search uploaded documents for the specific benefits terms applicable to this executive.\n\nAddress expense reimbursement, stating that the company will reimburse reasonable and necessary business expenses incurred in performing duties, subject to documentation requirements and company policy.\n\n## Term, Termination, and Severance\n\nSpecify whether this is an at-will employment relationship or a fixed term agreement. If at-will, state clearly that either party may terminate the relationship at any time with or without cause, subject to notice requirements and severance provisions. If a fixed term, specify the initial term length and any automatic renewal provisions.\n\nDetail the various termination scenarios with precision. For termination by the company for Cause, define \"Cause\" comprehensively to include willful misconduct, material breach of agreement, conviction of felony or crime involving moral turpitude, fraud or embezzlement, material violation of company policy, and continued failure to perform duties after written notice. For termination without Cause, specify the notice period required (typically 30-60 days for executives) or payment in lieu of notice.\n\nFor resignation by the executive, distinguish between resignation for Good Reason and voluntary resignation without Good Reason. Define \"Good Reason\" to include material diminution of duties or responsibilities, material reduction in compensation, relocation beyond a specified distance, and material breach by the company. Require the executive to provide notice of Good Reason circumstances and allow the company a cure period (typically 30 days).\n\nAddress termination due to death or Disability, defining Disability with reference to the company's long-term disability plan or as inability to perform essential functions for a specified period (commonly 90-180 consecutive days).\n\nFor each termination scenario, specify the severance entitlements. Common structures include: (1) for termination without Cause or resignation for Good Reason, payment of 12-24 months base salary, pro-rated bonus, COBRA continuation, and accelerated vesting of equity; (2) for termination for Cause or voluntary resignation, accrued but unpaid salary and benefits only; (3) for death or Disability, similar treatment to without Cause termination. Condition severance payments on execution of a release of claims and continued compliance with restrictive covenants.\n\nResearch the enforceability standards for severance provisions in the applicable jurisdiction, particularly regarding release requirements and restrictive covenant consideration. Some states require separate consideration for post-employment restrictions.\n\n## Confidentiality, Intellectual Property, and Restrictive Covenants\n\nDraft comprehensive confidentiality obligations requiring the executive to maintain in strict confidence all proprietary and confidential information of the company, including trade secrets, customer lists, financial information, business strategies, product development plans, and any information marked or reasonably understood to be confidential. Specify that these obligations survive termination indefinitely for trade secrets and for a reasonable period (typically 3-5 years) for other confidential information.\n\nInclude an intellectual property assignment provision stating that all inventions, discoveries, works of authorship, and other intellectual property created by the executive during employment and relating to the company's business or using company resources are the sole property of the company. Require the executive to assist in securing patents, copyrights, and other protections.\n\nDraft non-competition and non-solicitation covenants carefully, as enforceability varies significantly by jurisdiction. Research the specific state's standards for reasonableness in scope, duration, and geographic limitation. A typical executive non-compete might restrict competing activities for 12-24 months post-termination within a defined geographic area or market segment. Non-solicitation provisions typically prohibit soliciting employees, customers, or business partners for 12-24 months post-termination.\n\nVerify through legal research whether the jurisdiction requires additional consideration for restrictive covenants beyond continued employment, whether certain executives are exempt from non-compete restrictions, and what blue-pencil or reformation doctrines apply. Some states like California severely restrict non-competes, while others enforce reasonable restrictions. Tailor your language to maximize enforceability in the governing jurisdiction.\n\nInclude a non-disparagement clause requiring both parties to refrain from making negative statements about the other, with appropriate exceptions for truthful testimony and legal compliance.\n\n## Governing Law, Dispute Resolution, and Remedies\n\nSpecify the governing law clearly, typically the state where the company is headquartered or where the executive will primarily work. Research whether the chosen jurisdiction has any specific requirements or limitations for executive employment agreements.\n\nAddress dispute resolution through a carefully structured process. Consider including a mandatory mediation provision requiring good-faith mediation before litigation or arbitration. For arbitration, specify the administering organization (such as JAMS or AAA), the location, the number of arbitrators, and whether arbitration is binding. Address who bears the costs and whether the prevailing party recovers attorneys' fees.\n\nAlternatively, if disputes will be resolved through litigation, specify the exclusive jurisdiction and venue, typically in state or federal courts in a particular county or district. Include a waiver of jury trial if desired by both parties.\n\nGiven the nature of restrictive covenants and confidentiality obligations, include a specific provision acknowledging that breach would cause irreparable harm for which monetary damages are inadequate, and that the company is entitled to seek injunctive relief without posting bond. This language supports obtaining temporary restraining orders and preliminary injunctions for covenant violations.\n\n## Miscellaneous and Boilerplate Provisions\n\nInclude standard but important miscellaneous provisions. An entire agreement clause should state that this agreement constitutes the complete understanding between the parties and supersedes all prior negotiations, understandings, and agreements, whether written or oral. Specify that amendments must be in writing signed by both parties.\n\nA severability provision should state that if any provision is found invalid or unenforceable, the remaining provisions continue in full force, and the invalid provision should be reformed to be enforceable to the maximum extent permitted. This is particularly important for restrictive covenants.\n\nAddress assignment, stating that the executive cannot assign their rights or delegate duties under the agreement, but the company may assign the agreement to a successor or affiliate, with the agreement binding on successors and assigns.\n\nInclude a notice provision specifying how formal notices must be delivered (typically in writing via certified mail, overnight courier, or email to specified addresses) and when notices are deemed received.\n\nAdd a waiver provision clarifying that failure to enforce any provision does not waive the right to enforce it later, and that waivers must be in writing.\n\nConsider including provisions addressing withholding and tax compliance, stating that all compensation is subject to required withholding and that the executive is responsible for tax consequences. If the executive may be subject to Section 409A of the Internal Revenue Code (governing deferred compensation), include specific compliance language stating the agreement is intended to comply with or be exempt from Section 409A, and providing that payments may be delayed if necessary to avoid penalties for specified employees of public companies.\n\nInclude a counterparts clause permitting execution in multiple counterparts, each constituting an original, and allowing electronic signatures.\n\n## Signature Block and Execution\n\nProvide a professional signature block with spaces for the company to sign (typically by an authorized officer such as the CEO or Board Chair, with their title indicated) and for the executive to sign. Include lines for printed names and dates of execution beneath each signature line.\n\nConsider whether the agreement should be acknowledged before a notary, though this is typically not required for employment agreements unless they will be recorded or have specific enforceability concerns.\n\n## Final Document Assembly and Review\n\nOnce you have gathered all necessary information from uploaded documents, researched applicable legal standards and best practices, and drafted each section with appropriate specificity, create a complete, professionally formatted Employment Agreement document. The document should flow logically, use consistent defined terms, employ clear section numbering, and present a polished final product ready for attorney review and negotiation.\n\nEnsure all factual information is accurate and sourced from the uploaded documents, all legal provisions reflect current best practices and jurisdictional requirements, and the overall agreement protects both parties' interests while being fair and enforceable. The final document should be comprehensive enough to govern the employment relationship while remaining clear and understandable to both sophisticated parties.",
